This patch adds the files from PR #2203 but edits a test logging function that was causing test failures in GCC_ARM.

The file in question is `features/storage/cfstore/source/cfstore_test.h`. It removes a call to `snprintf` inside of the `CFSTORE_TEST_UTEST_MESSAGE` macro defined in that file. This allows tests to pass with GCC_ARM. When tested locally, the cfstore tests were passing when built with the ARM and IAR toolchains as well.

@simonqhughes

The `target_overrides` config option only allows to add/remove custom features (`FEATURE_*`). Other symbols can only be overridden (the symbol needs to be there in the first place).

This means that it is not possible for `target_overrides` to add/remove a new label (`TARGET_*`), a new custom macro or a new `DEVICE_HAS_*` macro.

**How to reproduce**

If in an application you override the K64F target, this is allowed:

``` json
{
    "target_overrides": {
        "K64F": {
            "target.features_add": ["UVISOR"]
        }
    }
}
```

but this is not (compile error):

``` json
{
    "target_overrides": {
        "K64F": {
            "target.features_add": ["UVISOR"],
            "target.extra_labels_add": ["UVISOR_SUPPORTED"]
        }
    }
}
```

**Additional notes**

This feature was originally available for custom targets (which BTW are not working any more, see #2196 and [this related issue](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-cli/issues/281)).

In the case of the uVisor hello-world example and other similar applications, though, it is not ideal to define custom targets. `target_overrides` are more natural.

This is a blocker for the release of the uVisor hello-world application.

